‘With the resignation of Head Coach Johnny Majors and the
recent follies of the Pitt football program, we believe that not only is
it necessary that Athletic Director Steve Pederson hire the right man,
but also that he must do it quickly.

And we believe that the right man is Matt Cavanaugh. Not only
was Cavanaugh MVP of the 1977 Sugar Bowl, the game which

, solidiﬁed Pitt’s 1976 National Championship, he’s currently the

quarterback coach for the San Francisco 49ers. He deals with Steve
Young and Elvis Grbac on a day-to-day basis.

Although Cavanaugh’s name doesn’t command the attention of
a Mike Ditka, who hasn’t coached since 1992, or a Tony Dorsett,
who’s never coached anything, it’s pretty easy to see that he’s a capa-
ble, hard—working man who has some serious connections to this
school.

Over the last few weeks, names like Joe Walton of Robert
Morris College, JlII1 Tressel of Youngstown State; and good ol’
Jackie Sherrill, whose 1980-81 Pitt team is considered one of the
greatest ever, have surfaced as potential candidates.

God help us. v ‘

Walton couldn’t teach Bubby Brister how to throw a spiral dur-
ing his reign as Steeler offensive coordinator, and you saw the job he
did with some fairly talented New York Jets teams in the early ‘80s.
How could he turn around this program? Tressel did a marvelous job
at Youngstown State, but he doesn’t have the name power to recap-
ture the Westem Pennsylvanian recruits that we now lose to Penn
State and Ohio State. Sherrill owns Pitt’s best all-time winning per-
centage, but his heart isn’t at Pitt.

Cavanaugh’s heart is here. Earlier in the year, The Pitt News
contacted Cavanaugh after his name surfaced as a candidate for the
Athletic Director’s position. He denied it and told us, “I’m just a

coach.” The goal of any coach is to be a head coach, a position of '

incredible esteem when a team wins or a position of public scorn
when a team loses. it

With the legwork that Majors accomplished in his second
tenure here‘ (stadium renovations and improved recruiting),
Cavanaugh has the potential to continue leading this program back
to glory, or at least a winning season.

 

