other hand, you will likely still use
paper ballots, which take just a little
longer, if you live in the GOP—dorni-
nated center of the state. I remem-
bered that two years ago, when at
around 9:30 p.m. the media correctly
projected Rick Santorum the winner
over Hanis Wotford for the U.S.
Senate, even though Wofford was
actually ahead in the actual vote
count at the time.

However, some folks apparent-
ly forgot.

That happened in the races for

attomey general and state treasurer,

when the Associated Press declared
Joe Kohn and Mina Baker Knoll, the
respective Democratic candidates,
the victors at around 11:30 pm. In
fact, at Knoll’s party, the campaign
had even posted vote totals on a
screen to the rightof the podium
which gave her about 54 percent.

But by the time Moushey got
me home at around 1 am.
Wednesday, both races turned into a
deadheat—and Fisher and Barbara
Hafer would eventually end up in the
winner’s circle.

And arguably the most embar-
rassing — and hilarious — gaffe
pulled by the media had to come
from KDKA-TV, which at 9:30 p.m.
had projected Mike McCormick the
winner over Frank Mascara in a local

congressional race. However, just’

five minutes later, anchor Stacy
Smith, mumbling that “I need to
wipe the egg off my face,” admitted
that the totals he read only represent-
ed the Allegheny County portion of
that district, which extends into

Washington and Greene counties.-

(Mascara won, by the way.)

Solutions? Run either regular
programming or the results of state
or local races starting at, say, 9
o’clock and defer the presidential
race until the 10 or 11 o’clock news
(depending on the time zone). Or
perhaps the news bureaus could
report out of Los Angeles or San
Francisco where the polls don’t close
until late. Okay, I know that folks on
the East Coast, depending on what
time they go to bed, might not get the
results until they wake up the next
morning. But hey —— we do want to
get the story right, don’t we?

It would help to remember the
old Yogi Berra—ism “It ain’t over ‘til
it’s over.”

